explanation:
ARGCHECK - The target function calls ARGCHECK(name,...). Need the macro/definition to know exactly what checks are done (null check, use of name, any string functions) to determine if a subsequent string operation could read beyond the buffer.

LENGTHCHECK - The function calls LENGTHCHECK(name, OS_MAX_API_NAME, ...). The LENGTHCHECK implementation must be inspected to see whether it uses strlen/strnlen or other string functions and whether it enforces a safe upper bound before any string operation.

OS_MAX_API_NAME - The LENGTHCHECK uses OS_MAX_API_NAME as the limit. The actual numeric limit is required to decide whether the length checks are sufficient to prevent out-of-bounds accesses.

OS_ObjectIdGetByName - The target calls this function with the name pointer. If that function (or the path it calls) performs any string operations on the name (copy, compare, etc.), those implementations must be examined to ensure they do not access beyond the name buffer.

OS_ObjectIdGetBySearch - OS_ObjectIdGetByName calls this function (per the call graph). Any string handling performed there is relevant to the safety of operations on the name parameter.

OS_ObjectIdRelease - The target calls this after getting the token. Include its implementation in case it manipulates name-related data (freeing, copying, or other string ops) that could affect safety analysis.

strlen, strnlen, strcpy, strncpy, memcpy, memcmp, strcmp, strncmp - These are the common <string.h> functions that may be used directly or indirectly by ARGCHECK, LENGTHCHECK, OS_ObjectIdGetByName/OS_ObjectIdGetBySearch/OS_ObjectIdRelease. To determine MISRA compliance for this target, the exact usage of any of these functions (which can cause out-of-bounds reads/writes) must be examined: which functions are called, with what length arguments, and whether sufficient bounds checks are present.

Note: The above list focuses on symbols that affect whether any standard string.h function is used unsafely on the 'name' pointer. Inspecting the actual definitions/implementations of these symbols will allow a precise determination of whether the target function (including the call chain it invokes) violates the quoted MISRA rule.
